  "local_port": 48768,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are all time best movies to watch?",
  "response": "Creating a definitive list of the \"all-time best movies\" can be subjective, as personal tastes, cultural backgrounds, and varying criteria for what makes a film great all play a role. However, the following list includes some widely acclaimed films across different genres and eras, celebrated for their storytelling, direction, acting, and overall impact on cinema:\n\n### **Classic Masterpieces**\n\n1. **_Citizen Kane_** (1941)\n   - Directed by Orson Welles, this film is often lauded for its innovative storytelling and cinematography, exploring the complex life of a publishing tycoon.\n\n2. **_Casablanca_** (1942)\n   - A romantic drama set against the backdrop of World War II, featuring iconic performances by Humphrey Bogart and Ingrid Bergman.\n\n3. **_The Godfather_** (1972) & **_The Godfather Part II_** (1974)\n   - Directed by Francis Ford Coppola, these films delve deep into the lives of an Italian-American mafia family, blending crime, drama, and intricate character studies.\n\n### **Modern Classics**\n\n4. **_Schindler's List_** (1993)\n   - Steven Spielberg's powerful portrayal of Oskar Schindler, a man who saved hundreds of Jews during the Holocaust, combining historical significance with emotional depth.\n\n5. **_Pulp Fiction_** (1994)\n   - Quentin Tarantino's groundbreaking nonlinear narrative intertwines multiple stories of crime and redemption, noted for its sharp dialogue and eclectic characters.\n\n6. **_The Shawshank Redemption_** (1994)\n   - Directed by Frank Darabont, this inspiring tale of hope and friendship within a prison setting has become a beloved favorite for many.\n\n### **Science Fiction & Fantasy**\n\n7. **_2001: A Space Odyssey_** (1968)\n   - Stanley Kubrick's visionary film explores humanity, artificial intelligence, and the unknowns of space with groundbreaking visual effects and philosophical depth.\n\n8. **_Star Wars: Episode IV \u2013 A New Hope_** (1977)\n   - George Lucas's epic space opera revolutionized special effects and storytelling in cinema, creating a beloved universe that continues to expand.\n\n9. **_The Lord of the Rings_** Trilogy (2001\u20132003)\n   - Directed by Peter Jackson, these films bring J.R.R. Tolkien's expansive fantasy world to life with stunning visuals and a compelling narrative.\n\n### **Contemporary Highlights**\n\n10. **_The Dark Knight_** (2008)\n    - Christopher Nolan's second installment in his Batman trilogy is praised for its complex characters, especially Heath Ledger's iconic performance as the Joker.\n\n11. **_Inception_** (2010)\n    - Another Nolan masterpiece, this mind-bending thriller delves into dreams and reality with intricate plotlines and spectacular visual effects.\n\n12. **_Parasite_** (2019)\n    - Directed by Bong Joon-ho, this South Korean film masterfully blends social commentary, dark humor, and suspense, earning widespread international acclaim.\n\n### **Animated Excellence**\n\n13. **_Spirited Away_** (2001)\n    - Hayao Miyazaki's enchanting animated film follows a young girl's journey through a magical world, celebrated for its imaginative storytelling and stunning animation.\n\n14. **_Toy Story_** Series (1995\u20132019)\n    - Pixar's groundbreaking animated films explore themes of friendship, growth, and the passage of time, beloved by audiences of all ages.\n\n### **Dramatic Essentials**\n\n15. **_Forrest Gump_** (1994)\n    - Directed by Robert Zemeckis, this heartwarming story follows a man's extraordinary life journey through pivotal moments in American history.\n\n16. **_Fight Club_** (1999)\n    - David Fincher's provocative film examines consumerism, identity, and rebellion, leaving a lasting impact on popular culture.\n\n### **International Gems**\n\n17. **_Am\u00e9lie_** (2001)\n    - A whimsical French film that captures the life of a young woman in Paris as she seeks to make the lives of those around her better.\n\n18. **_City of God_** (2002)\n    - This Brazilian film offers a raw and gripping look at life in the favelas of Rio de Janeiro, praised for its dynamic storytelling and realism.\n\n### **Documentary Standouts**\n\n19. **_Planet Earth_** (2006) & **_Planet Earth II_** (2016)\n    - While technically a series, these documentaries produced by the BBC offer breathtaking visuals of our planet, raising awareness about environmental conservation.\n\n20. **_13th_** (2016)\n    - Directed by Ava DuVernay, this powerful documentary explores the history of racial inequality in the United States, particularly focusing on the nation's prisons.\n\n---\n\n**Note:** This list is by no means exhaustive, and many other exceptional films could be included based on different criteria and personal preferences. Exploring various genres and international cinema can provide a richer understanding and appreciation of the art of filmmaking.",
